Passengers enter Hong Kong at the Shenzhen Bay Port in September, 2021. Photo: IC China's Ministry of Public Security said it will do its best to implement the central government's policy to benefit the customs clearance into mainland, travel, study, employment and living in the Chinese mainland for the residents of the Hong Kong and Macao special administrative regions (SARs) with policies and other supporting measures. On Monday, the Ministry of Public Security held an enlarged meeting of the Party Committee during which the importance of solving deep-seated problems closely related to the interests of the people of Hong Kong and Macao and promoting the development and progress of social causes in Hong Kong and Macao, were stressed.The Ministry of Public Security has pledged to fully implement the central government's policies and improve policies and measures to facilitate customs clearance between the SARs and the mainland, vehicle travel, document processing and relocating to the mainland to study, work and live.After the requirement for entry into the Chinese mainland was shortened to seven days of centralized isolation and three days of home isolation, a large number of residents have been arriving in Shenzhen from Hong Kong every day as prices of quarantine hotels rise.On July 7, Shenzhen added additional quarantine hotel rooms for eight specific groups, including those aged 70 or above and children under 14 without guardians in the SAR, Hong Kong media outlet The Standard reported. Some media reported that quarantine-free travel between Hong Kong and the mainland is expected in a few months.The Ministry also voiced firm support for the Hong Kong Police Force and other forces to play a major role in the main responsibility to continuously consolidate the social order of Hong Kong a stable and positive situation.The Ministry said it will give full play to the functions of public security organs to maintain national security and long-term peace and stability in Hong Kong and Macao and ensure that the cause of "one country, two systems" steadily moves forward.Global Times